</p></div>"}

For silk flowers, choose ones that have non-toxic dyes. If you can't ascertain this, don't use them unless the bowl is going to be used for non-food purposes (such as for holding cans of drink). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8e/810666-9-2.jpg/v4-459px-810666-9-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8e/810666-9-2.jpg/v4-759px-810666-9-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

For citrus rounds, choose suitably sized oranges, limes, lemons, etc. and cut into perfect round sections. Cut enough to go around the bowl. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/810666-9-3.jpg/v4-459px-810666-9-3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/810666-9-3.jpg/v4-759px-810666-9-3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

The water should shift up the side gap, which will be about 1 inch (2.5cm) in thickness. The flowers will be caught both underneath and along the sides of the bowl as well; add more flowers to the gap, pushing them in with the wooden skewer. It can be as packed with flowers as you like, or left more sparse. If you're using citrus rounds, this is the time to slip them into the gap at equal intervals around the gap. Use the wooden skewer to align the citrus rounds. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/810666-11-1.jpg/v4-459px-810666-11-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/810666-11-1.jpg/v4-759px-810666-11-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons</a>
</p></div>"}

Large globs of poster tack can be rolled up and stuck between each bowl edge to maintain an exact distance. You'll need to mold the tack over the rims to keep it in place. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/810666-11-2.jpg/v4-459px-810666-11-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5e/810666-11-2.jpg/v4-759px-810666-11-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Image by: Uploader<br>
